{{Infobox person | name = Josiah Ransome-Kuti | honorific_suffix = | image = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Josiah Jesse Ransome-Kuti | birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1855|6|1}} | birth_place = [[Abeokuta]], [[Ogun State]], [[Nigeria]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|1930|9|4|1855|6|1}} | death_place = | death_cause = | nationality = [[Nigerian]] | alma_mater = | occupation = {{flatlist| *[[clergyman]] *[[educationist]] *[[composer]]}} | years_active = 1871–1930 | known_for = | notable_works = <!-- produces label "Notable work"; may be verridden by |credits=, which produces label "Notable credit(s)"; or by |works=, which produces label "Works" --> | spouse = {{marriage|Bertha Anny Erinade Olubi|1882}} | relations = | children = {{Collapsible list |titlestyle=font-weight:normal; background:transparent; text-align:left; |title = 3 |1= Grace Eniola Ransome-Kuti|2= Azariah Olusegun Ransome-Kuti |3= [[Israel Oludotun Ransome-Kuti]] }} | parents = Likoye Kuti, Ekidan Efupeyin | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | module = | signature = | signature_size = | signature_alt = | footnotes = }}
'''Josiah Jesse Ransome-Kuti''' (1 June 1855 – 4 September 1930) was a [[Nigerian]] [[clergyman]] and [[Composer|music composer]].<ref name="Ádésóyè2015">{{cite book|author=Ádébáyò Ádésóyè|title=Scientific Pilgrimage: 'The Life and times of Emeritus Professor V.A Oyenuga'. D.Sc, FAS, CFR Nigeria’s first Emeritus Professor and Africa’s first Agriculture Professor.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OdbBBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT75|date=25 March 2015|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-5049-3785-6|pages=75–}}</ref> He was known for setting Christian hymns to indigenous music,<ref name="Johnson-OdimMba1997">{{cite book|author1=Cheryl Johnson-Odim|author2=Nina Emma Mba|title=For Women and the Nation: Funmilayo Ransome-Kuti of Nigeria|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZyMyspsywPsC&pg=PA32|year=1997|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-06613-9|pages=32–}}</ref> and for writing Christian hymns in [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]].
==Early life and career== Born on 1 June 1855 in Igbein, [[Abeokuta]], [[Ogun State]], to an [[Egba people|Egba]] family, Josiah Ransome-Kuti was baptized in 1859. He enrolled as a student into the Church Missionary Society Training Institution, Abeokuta, before proceeding to the Church Missionary Society Training Institute, [[Lagos State|Lagos]] in 1871.<ref name=dacb>{{cite web|url=http://www.dacb.org/stories/nigeria/ransome-kuti_josiah.html|title=Ransome-Kuti, Josiah Jesse|work=Dictionary of African Christian Biography|date=|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>
Shortly after completing his education at the Church Missionary Society Training Institute, Lagos, Ransome-Kuti was employed as a teacher at St. Peter's School, Ake, Abeokuta, and then left in 1879 to teach music at the CMS Girls School, Lagos, where he met his wife Bertha Anny Erinade Olubi.<ref name=dacb/> In 1891, he was made [[catechist]] at the Gbagura Church Parsonage, Abeokuta before he founded Gbagura Church, a local church where he converted people to the Christian faith through his versatility in rendering [[English language|English]] gospel hymns into indigenous gospel songs.<ref name=dacb/><ref name="UwechueLimited1991">{{cite book|author1=Raph Uwechue|author2=Africa Books Limited|title=Makers of Modern Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YkEOAQAAMAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Africa Journal Limited}}</ref>
Ransome-Kuti became a deacon in 1895, ordained a priest in 1897 and was appointed district judge from 1902 to 1906.<ref name=dacb/> In 1911, he was appointed pastor of St. Peter's Cathedral Church, Ake after previously serving as superintendent of the Abeokuta Church Mission.<ref>H. Zell, C. H. Bundy and V. Coulon (eds), ''A New Reader's Guide to African Literature'', rev. edn, (London : Heinemann, 1983).</ref>
In 1922, he was made [[Canon (priest)|canon]] of the Cathedral Church of Christ, Lagos and in 1925, he became the first Nigerian to release a record album after he recorded several [[Yoruba language]] hymns in [[gramophone record|gramophone]] through [[Zonophone|Zonophone Records]].<ref name="Ádésóyè2015"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/dec/11/fela-kuti-great-dynasties-ian-sansom|title=Great Dynasties: The Ransome-Kutis|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Sansom|first=Ian|date=11 December 2015|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>
==Personal life== He married Bertha Erina Olubi in 1882. They had three children; Grace Eniola, Azariah Olusegun and [[Israel Oludotun Ransome-Kuti|Israel Oludotun]]. His descendants would go on to constitute the [[Ransome-Kuti family]].
