{{Distinguish|Kham language}} {{Infobox language |name=Khams Tibetan |altname=Kham-Hor |nativename=Khampa |region=[[China]], [[Bhutan]], [[Tibet Autonomous Region]], [[Amdo]], [[Qinghai]], [[Sichuan]], [[Yunnan]] |speakers=1.4 million <!--1,400,630--> |date=1994 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Tibeto-Kanauri languages|Tibeto-Kanauri]] ? |fam3=[[Bodish languages|Bodish]] |fam4=[[Tibetic languages|Tibetic]] |script=[[Tibetan alphabet]] | lc1 = khg |ld1=Khams | lc2 = kbg |ld2=Khamba<ref>George van Driem, ''Languages of the Himalayas'', p 892</ref> | lc3 = tsk |ld3=[[Tseku language|Tseku]] |notice=IPA |glotto=kham1299 |glottorefname=Khams–Hor }}
'''Khams Tibetan''' ({{bo|w=Khams skad|s=Khamké}}) is the [[Tibetic languages|Tibetic language]] used by the majority of the people in [[Kham]], which is now divided between the eastern part of [[Tibet Autonomous Region]], the southern part of Qinghai, the western part of [[Sichuan]], and the northwestern part of [[Yunnan]], China. It is one of the six main spoken Tibetic languages, the other four being [[Central Tibetan language]], [[Amdo Tibetan|Amdo]], [[Ladakhi language|Ladakhi]] , [[Dzongkha]] and [[Balti language|Balti]]. These Tibetic languages share the same written script, but their pronunciations, vocabularies and grammars are different. These differences may have emerged due to geographical isolation of the regions of Tibet. Khams Tibetan is used alongside [[Standard Tibetan]] and Amdo Tibetan in broadcasting. Khams Tibetan is not [[Mutual intelligibility|mutually intelligible]] with other Tibetic languages.
Like Central Tibetan, Khams Tibetan is a tonal language.{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}
Khampa Tibetan is also spoken by about 1,000 people in two enclaves in eastern [[Bhutan]], the descendants of pastoral yak-herding communities.<ref name=vanDriem93>{{cite web|url=http://repository.forcedmigration.org/pdf/?pid=fmo:3003 |format=PDF |last=van Driem |first=George L. |authorlink=George van Driem |title=Language Policy in Bhutan |publisher=[[School of Oriental and African Studies|SOAS]] |location=[[London]] |year=1993 |accessdate=2011-01-18}}</ref>
==Dialects== There are five dialects of Khams Tibetan proper:
* '''Central Khams''', spoken in [[Dêgê County]] and [[Chamdo]] * '''Southern Khams''', spoken in the [[Diqing Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture]]. There are several subdialects due to the mountainous terrain, as well as contact with neighboring language communities for trade. * '''Northern''' or '''Northeastern Khams''', spoken in [[Nangqên County]] and [[Yushu Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture]] * '''Eastern Khams''', spoken in [[Kangding]] * '''''Hor''''', or '''Western Khams''', spoken in [[Nagqu Prefecture]] * The [[Gêrzê County|Gêrzê]] dialect is sometimes considered '''Western Khams'''
These have relatively low mutual intelligibility, but are close enough that they are usually considered a single language. Khamba and [[Tseku language|Tseku]] are more divergent, but classified with Khams by Tournadre (2013).
Several other languages are spoken by Tibetans in the Khams region: [[Dongwang Tibetan language]] and the [[Rgyalrong languages]].<ref>N. Tournadre (2005) "L'aire linguistique tibétaine et ses divers dialectes." ''Lalies'', 2005, n°25, p.&nbsp;7–56 [http://tournadre.nicolas.free.fr/fichiers/2005-aire.pdf]</ref>
The phonologies and vocabularies of the Bodgrong, Dartsendo, dGudzong, Khyungpo (Khromtshang), Lhagang Rangakha, Sangdam, Sogpho, sKobsteng, sPomtserag, Tsharethong, and Yangthang dialects of Kham Tibetan have been documented by Hiroyuki Suzuki.<ref>[http://www.aa.tufs.ac.jp/en/publications/aall ''Asian and African Languages and Linguistics'']</ref>
